Comment: I am actually not going to annotate this entire game. I am a bit sick lately and more sick because I just lost a game I should have won had it not been for my lack of seriousness at the end, and my telling myself "don't worry there is not checkmate he can pull on you for now". I do not think the game is necessarily eventful in any particular way until about move 25 or so. Both my opponent and I make decent moves as well as mistakes and blunders along the way. It is my big blunder at the end that I hope offers some lessons to some poor soul out there.

and he does not take my bishop. Yet I neglect to move it.
I move my queen instead. I notice my blunder and figure that is it.
But instead of taking with his pawn (maybe he did not want to) he attacks with his knight, and finally I move my bishop.
So it is to be a slightly spacey game on both our parts it seems.

Here is where I blow it. I know he is going to take my pawn on H3. But I feel like I am in one of those games on Youtube now, and the commenter goes "But Courtney dismisses the pawn and allows the foolish Bobby Fischer to fall into his trap." I figure I will be okay, that him checkmating me is all but impossible. Really, that is my thinking at this point. I will take the other pawn and advance my pawns and promote one or maybe two of them. I feel I have the advantage of a soon to be promoted pawn on my side.

Saw this coming (or the bishop to G2) but am not concerned. Figure I will move my rook out. But a some time goes by before the enxt move and I sort of forget about the game in away. After unchecking my king I forget about how good repositioning my rook seemed earlier in the day, or the day before.
